events.description: Liu Bei, Chinese warlord, proclaims himself emperor of Shu Han, the successor of the Han dynasty.
events.html: • 221 – Liu Bei, Chinese warlord, proclaims himself emperor of Shu Han, the successor of the Han dynasty.

events.description: Emperor Valentinian II is assassinated while advancing into Gaul against the Frankish usurper Arbogast. He is found hanging in his residence at Vienne.
events.html: • 392 – Emperor Valentinian II is assassinated while advancing into Gaul against the Frankish usurper Arbogast. He is found hanging in his residence at Vienne.

events.description: King Authari marries Theodelinda, daughter of the Bavarian duke Garibald I. A Catholic, she has great influence among the Lombard nobility.
events.html: • 589 – King Authari marries Theodelinda, daughter of the Bavarian duke Garibald I. A Catholic, she has great influence among the Lombard nobility.

events.description: Abd al-Rahman I, the founder of the Arab dynasty that ruled the greater part of Iberia for nearly three centuries, becomes emir of Cordova, Spain.
events.html: • 756 – Abd al-Rahman I, the founder of the Arab dynasty that ruled the greater part of Iberia for nearly three centuries, becomes emir of Cordova, Spain.[1]

events.description: Pope Innocent IV issues the papal bull ad extirpanda, which authorizes, but also limits, the torture of heretics in the Medieval Inquisition.
events.html: • 1252 – Pope Innocent IV issues the papal bull ad extirpanda, which authorizes, but also limits, the torture of heretics in the Medieval Inquisition.

events.description: Insurgent peasants led by Anabaptist pastor Thomas Müntzer were defeated at the Battle of Frankenhausen, ending the German Peasants' War in the Holy Roman Empire.
events.html: • 1525 – Insurgent peasants led by Anabaptist pastor Thomas Müntzer were defeated at the Battle of Frankenhausen, ending the German Peasants' War in the Holy Roman Empire.

events.description: Anne Boleyn, Queen of England, stands trial in London on charges of treason, adultery and incest; she is condemned to death by a specially-selected jury.
events.html: • 1536 – Anne Boleyn, Queen of England, stands trial in London on charges of treason, adultery and incest; she is condemned to death by a specially-selected jury.

events.description: Cape Cod is sighted by English navigator Bartholomew Gosnold.
events.html: • 1602 – Cape Cod is sighted by English navigator Bartholomew Gosnold.[2]

events.description: Johannes Kepler confirms his previously rejected discovery of the third law of planetary motion (he first discovered it on March 8 but soon rejected the idea after some initial calculations were made).
events.html: • 1618 – Johannes Kepler confirms his previously rejected discovery of the third law of planetary motion (he first discovered it on March 8 but soon rejected the idea after some initial calculations were made).

events.description: The Peace of Münster is ratified, by which Spain acknowledges Dutch sovereignty.
events.html: • 1648 – The Peace of Münster is ratified, by which Spain acknowledges Dutch sovereignty.

events.description: French Revolution: Maximilien Robespierre proposes the Self-denying Ordinance.
events.html: • 1791 – French Revolution: Maximilien Robespierre proposes the Self-denying Ordinance.

events.description: Opening of the first private mental health hospital in the United States, the Asylum for the Relief of Persons Deprived of the Use of Their Reason (now Friends Hospital, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania).
events.html: • 1817 – Opening of the first private mental health hospital in the United States, the Asylum for the Relief of Persons Deprived of the Use of Their Reason (now Friends Hospital, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania).

events.description: Francis Baily observes "Baily's beads" during an annular eclipse.
events.html: • 1836 – Francis Baily observes "Baily's beads" during an annular eclipse.

events.description: The Sicilian revolution of 1848 is finally extinguished.
events.html: • 1849 – The Sicilian revolution of 1848 is finally extinguished.

events.description: The Arana–Southern Treaty is ratified, ending "the existing differences" between Great Britain and Argentina.
events.html: • 1850 – The Arana–Southern Treaty is ratified, ending "the existing differences" between Great Britain and Argentina.

events.description: The first Australian gold rush is proclaimed, although the discovery had been made three months earlier.
events.html: • 1851 – The first Australian gold rush is proclaimed, although the discovery had been made three months earlier.

events.description: American Civil War: Battle of New Market, Virginia: Students from the Virginia Military Institute fight alongside the Confederate army to force Union General Franz Sigel out of the Shenandoah Valley.
events.html: • 1864 – American Civil War: Battle of New Market, Virginia: Students from the Virginia Military Institute fight alongside the Confederate army to force Union General Franz Sigel out of the Shenandoah Valley.

events.description: Pope Leo XIII defends workers' rights and property rights in the encyclical Rerum novarum, the beginning of modern Catholic social teaching.
events.html: • 1891 – Pope Leo XIII defends workers' rights and property rights in the encyclical Rerum novarum, the beginning of modern Catholic social teaching.

events.description: The city of Las Vegas is founded in Nevada, United States.
events.html: • 1905 – The city of Las Vegas is founded in Nevada, United States.[3]

events.description: In Standard Oil Co. of New Jersey v. United States, the United States Supreme Court declares Standard Oil to be an "unreasonable" monopoly under the Sherman Antitrust Act and orders the company to be broken up.
events.html: • 1911 – In Standard Oil Co. of New Jersey v. United States, the United States Supreme Court declares Standard Oil to be an "unreasonable" monopoly under the Sherman Antitrust Act and orders the company to be broken up.

events.description: More than 300 Chinese immigrants are killed in the Torreón massacre when the forces of the Mexican Revolution led by Emilio Madero take the city of Torreón from the Federales.
events.html: • 1911 – More than 300 Chinese immigrants are killed in the Torreón massacre when the forces of the Mexican Revolution led by Emilio Madero take the city of Torreón from the Federales.

events.description: The Finnish Civil War ends when the Whites took over Fort Ino, a Russian coastal artillery base on the Karelian Isthmus, from Russian troops.
events.html: • 1918 – The Finnish Civil War ends when the Whites took over Fort Ino, a Russian coastal artillery base on the Karelian Isthmus, from Russian troops.[4]

events.description: A seventeen-year-old farmworker, Jesse Washington, is infamously lynched in Waco, Texas, USA, after being convicted of rape and murder.
events.html: • 1916 – A seventeen-year-old farmworker, Jesse Washington, is infamously lynched in Waco, Texas, USA, after being convicted of rape and murder.[5]

events.description: The Winnipeg general strike begins. By 11:00, almost the whole working population of Winnipeg had walked off the job.
events.html: • 1919 – The Winnipeg general strike begins. By 11:00, almost the whole working population of Winnipeg had walked off the job.

events.description: Greek occupation of Smyrna. During the occupation, the Greek army kills or wounds 350 Turks; those responsible are punished by Greek commander Aristides Stergiades.
events.html: • 1919 – Greek occupation of Smyrna. During the occupation, the Greek army kills or wounds 350 Turks; those responsible are punished by Greek commander Aristides Stergiades.

events.description: A fire at the Cleveland Clinic in Cleveland, Ohio kills 123.
events.html: • 1929 – A fire at the Cleveland Clinic in Cleveland, Ohio kills 123.

events.description: In an attempted coup d'état, the Prime Minister of Japan Inukai Tsuyoshi is assassinated.
events.html: • 1932 – In an attempted coup d'état, the Prime Minister of Japan Inukai Tsuyoshi is assassinated.

events.description: All military aviation organizations within or under the control of the RLM of Germany were officially merged in a covert manner to form its Wehrmacht military's air arm, the Luftwaffe.
events.html: • 1933 – All military aviation organizations within or under the control of the RLM of Germany were officially merged in a covert manner to form its Wehrmacht military's air arm, the Luftwaffe.

events.description: A self coup by prime minister Kārlis Ulmanis succeeded in Latvia, suspending its constitution and dissolving its Saeima.
events.html: • 1934 – A self coup by prime minister Kārlis Ulmanis succeeded in Latvia, suspending its constitution and dissolving its Saeima.[6]

events.description: USS Sailfish is recommissioned. It was originally the USS Squalus.
events.html: • 1940 – USS Sailfish is recommissioned. It was originally the USS Squalus.

events.description: World War II: The Battle of the Netherlands: After fierce fighting, the poorly trained and equipped Dutch troops surrender to Germany, marking the beginning of five years of occupation.
events.html: • 1940 – World War II: The Battle of the Netherlands: After fierce fighting, the poorly trained and equipped Dutch troops surrender to Germany, marking the beginning of five years of occupation.

events.description: Richard and Maurice McDonald open the first McDonald's restaurant.
events.html: • 1940 – Richard and Maurice McDonald open the first McDonald's restaurant.

events.description: First flight of the Gloster E.28/39 the first British and Allied jet aircraft.
events.html: • 1941 – First flight of the Gloster E.28/39 the first British and Allied jet aircraft.

events.description: World War II: In the United States, a bill creating the Women's Army Auxiliary Corps (WAAC) is signed into law.
events.html: • 1942 – World War II: In the United States, a bill creating the Women's Army Auxiliary Corps (WAAC) is signed into law.

events.description: Joseph Stalin dissolves the Comintern (or Third International).
events.html: • 1943 – Joseph Stalin dissolves the Comintern (or Third International).

events.description: World War II: The Battle of Poljana, the final skirmish in Europe is fought near Prevalje, Slovenia.
events.html: • 1945 – World War II: The Battle of Poljana, the final skirmish in Europe is fought near Prevalje, Slovenia.

events.description: Following the expiration of The British Mandate for Palestine, the Kingdom of Egypt, Transjordan, Lebanon, Syria, Iraq and Saudi Arabia invade Israel thus starting the 1948 Arab–Israeli War.
events.html: • 1948 – Following the expiration of The British Mandate for Palestine, the Kingdom of Egypt, Transjordan, Lebanon, Syria, Iraq and Saudi Arabia invade Israel thus starting the 1948 Arab–Israeli War.

events.description: At Malden Island in the Pacific Ocean, Britain tests its first hydrogen bomb in Operation Grapple.
events.html: • 1957 – At Malden Island in the Pacific Ocean, Britain tests its first hydrogen bomb in Operation Grapple.

events.description: Project Mercury: The launch of the final Mercury mission, Mercury-Atlas 9 with astronaut Gordon Cooper on board. He becomes the first American to spend more than a day in space, and the last American to go into space alone.
events.html: • 1963 – Project Mercury: The launch of the final Mercury mission, Mercury-Atlas 9 with astronaut Gordon Cooper on board. He becomes the first American to spend more than a day in space, and the last American to go into space alone.

events.description: President Richard Nixon appoints Anna Mae Hays and Elizabeth P. Hoisington the first female United States Army generals.
events.html: • 1970 – President Richard Nixon appoints Anna Mae Hays and Elizabeth P. Hoisington the first female United States Army generals.

events.description: The Ryukyu Islands, under U.S. military governance since its conquest in 1945, reverts to Japanese control.
events.html: • 1972 – The Ryukyu Islands, under U.S. military governance since its conquest in 1945, reverts to Japanese control.

events.description: Ma'alot massacre: Members of the Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine attack and take hostages at an Israeli school; a total of 31 people are killed, including 22 schoolchildren.

events.html: • 1976 – Aeroflot Flight 1802 crashes near Viktorivka, Chernihiv Raion, Chernihiv Oblast, killing 52.[7]

events.description: Soviet–Afghan War: After more than eight years of fighting, the Soviet Army begins to withdraw 115,000 troops from Afghanistan.
events.html: • 1988 – Soviet–Afghan War: After more than eight years of fighting, the Soviet Army begins to withdraw 115,000 troops from Afghanistan.

events.description: Édith Cresson becomes France's first female Prime Minister.
events.html: • 1991 – Édith Cresson becomes France's first female Prime Minister.

events.description: The United States government acknowledges the existence of the "Secret War" in Laos and dedicates the Laos Memorial in honor of Hmong and other "Secret War" veterans.
events.html: • 1997 – The United States government acknowledges the existence of the "Secret War" in Laos and dedicates the Laos Memorial in honor of Hmong and other "Secret War" veterans.

events.description: The Space Shuttle Atlantis launches on STS-84 to dock with the Russian space station Mir.
events.html: • 1997 – The Space Shuttle Atlantis launches on STS-84 to dock with the Russian space station Mir.[8]

events.description: A CSX EMD SD40-2 rolls out of a train yard in Walbridge, Ohio, with 47 freight cars, including some tank cars with flammable chemical, after its engineer fails to reboard it after setting a yard switch. It travels south driverless for 66 miles (106 km) until it was brought to a halt near Kenton. The incident became the inspiration for the 2010 film Unstoppable.
events.html: • 2001 – A CSX EMD SD40-2 rolls out of a train yard in Walbridge, Ohio, with 47 freight cars, including some tank cars with flammable chemical, after its engineer fails to reboard it after setting a yard switch.
